---
import InsideLayout from '../../layouts/InsideLayout.astro';
import PageLede from '../../components/silo/PageLede.astro';

const viewerName = Astro.locals.viewerName ?? '';
---

{/*
  NO CORPUS — Diego writes from scratch.
*/}

<InsideLayout
  title="Team & Velocity"
  chapter="07"
  viewerName={viewerName}
  prev={{ num: '06', title: 'Roadmap & Risks', href: '/inside/roadmap' }}
>
  <h1>Who decides, how fast we ship</h1>
  <PageLede>Today Silo is a one-person company. I set product direction, write the code, and use AI as leverage inside the build loop rather than as a substitute for judgment.</PageLede>

  <h2>Team</h2>
  <p>
    I am a practicing Brazilian lawyer, admitted under OAB/PR 96.036, with
    work across corporate and litigation matters. I am also the person
    writing the software. That combination is not a branding line. It is the
    reason the product keeps gravitating toward real workflow pain instead of
    generic AI demo logic.
  </p>
  <p>
    Today the team is me. There is no management layer being assembled ahead
    of validation, and there is no artificial org chart to make the company
    look larger than it is. The practitioner-as-builder bet is that many of
    the early errors in legal AI are errors of problem definition, not raw
    execution capacity. I would rather stay small while the core workflow is
    still hardening, then add people in response to a proved bottleneck.
  </p>

  <h2>Operating model</h2>
  <p>
    The operating model is short-loop by design. I prefer to resolve
    architecture and product questions close to the code, with a working
    example, a narrower interface, or a real case run, instead of a long
    planning ceremony. That keeps decisions falsifiable. If something is not
    legible in the product, it is usually not clear enough yet.
  </p>
  <p>
    AI is integrated into the build loop as leverage: drafting alternatives,
    pressure-testing assumptions, reviewing code, and accelerating the
    boring parts of implementation. The legal and product judgment still
    stays with me. That is why a one-person team can move quickly here: the
    system does not need to be re-explained across multiple roles before a
    change ships.
  </p>

  <h2>Cadence</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      On the public surface alone, this repo logged 10 commits between April
      4 and April 8, 2026. The private engine work sits outside that count.
    </li>
    <li>
      The portal project logged 14 production deployments in the last 18
      days on Vercel, which is roughly 23 production releases per month at
      the current pace.
    </li>
    <li>
      A sprint-sized product cycle here usually means 6-8 explicit
      decisions. The gated portal cycle alone resolved 8 open architecture
      questions before shipping.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What this document does not cover</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Detailed hiring plans</li>
    <li>Compensation structure</li>
    <li>Equity and ownership details</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Those are available on request where they matter to the discussion.</p>
</InsideLayout>
